{{Infobox ecoregion | name = Bahia coastal forests | image = Monte Pascoal Vista.jpg | image_size = | image_alt = | image_caption = [[Monte Pascoal National Park]], [[Bahia]], [[Brazil]]. | country = {{BRA}} | country1 = | country2 = | state = [[Bahia]] | state1 = [[Espírito Santo]] | border = [[Serra do Mar coastal forests]] | border1 = [[Bahia interior forests]] | border2 = [[Pernambuco coastal forests]] | bird_species = 466<ref name = "Atlas"> {{cite book |last1 = Hoekstra |first1 = J. M. |last2 = Molnar |first2 = J. L. |last3 = Jennings |first3 = M. |last4 = Revenga |first4 = C. |last5 = Spalding |first5 = M. D. |last6 = Boucher |first6 = T. M. |last7 = Robertson |first7 = J. C. |last8 = Heibel |first8 = T. J. |last9 = Ellison |first9 = K. |title = The Atlas of Global Conservation: Changes, Challenges, and Opportunities to Make a Difference |publisher = [[University of California Press]] |editor1-last = Molnar |editor1-first = J. L. |year = 2010 |isbn = 978-0-520-26256-0 |url=http://www.nature.org/ourscience/sciencefeatures/conservation-atlas-1.xml }}</ref> | mammal_species = 166<ref name = "Atlas"/> | habitat_loss = 95.0 | habitat_loss_ref = <ref>Viana, V. M., A.J. Tabanez, and J.L. Batista. 1997. Dynamics and restoration of forest fragments in the Brazilian Atlantic moist forest. Pages 351-365 in W.F. Laurance, and R.O. Bierregaard Jr, editors, Tropical forest remnants: ecology, management, and conservation of fragmented communities. University of Chicago Press, Chicago.</ref> | protected = 1.78 | protected_ref = <ref name = "Atlas"/> | area = 109815 | biome = [[Atlantic Forest]] | map = Bahia coastal forests WWF.png | map_size = 240 | map_alt = | map_caption = Localization of Bahia coastal forests ecorregion as delineated by [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]]. }}
The '''Bahia coastal forests''' are a [[tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests|tropical moist broadleaf forest]] [[ecoregion]] of eastern [[Brazil]], part of the larger [[Atlantic Forest]] region.
==Setting== The Bahia coastal forests occupy a belt approximately {{convert|150|km|mi|abbr=on}} wide along the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] coast of eastern Brazil, in the states of [[Bahia]] and [[Espirito Santo]]. The [[Itapicuru River]] forms the northern boundary of the ecoregion, which extends south to near the [[Itapemirim River]]. The ecoregion is bounded on the east by the [[Atlantic Ocean]] and the enclaves of the [[Atlantic Coast restingas]] forests and [[Bahia mangroves]]. To the west, the forests transition to the drier [[Bahia interior forests]].
The forests cover Tertiary sedimentary plateaus extending from near the seacoast westward to the lower slopes of the [[Serra da Mantiqueira]]. The prevalent soils are tropical nutrient-poor yellow-red [[latosol]] and [[podzol]]s.
===Climate=== The ecoregion has a [[tropical climate]] with annual rainfall ranging from 1,200 to 1,800&nbsp;mm, evenly distributed throughout the year. The southern portion of the ecoregion may experience a dry period from May through September.
==Flora== The four-tiered Atlantic evergreen moist forests are the predominant vegetation type.
==Fauna== [[File:Tamarin lion à tête dorée.jpg|thumb|left|[[Golden-headed lion tamarin]] is a primate endemic species of Bahia coastal forests.]] [[File:Bahia coastal forests WWF Satelite.jpg|thumb|right|Satellite picture of Bahia coastal forests ecoregion (yellow line). In this image is shown the desforestation degree of the ecoregion.]] Endangered mammals in the ecoregion include the [[maned three-toed sloth]] (''Bradypus torquatus'') and [[golden-headed lion tamarin]] (''Leontopithecus chrysomelas'').
==Conservation and threats== Less than 5% of the original forest cover remains intact. Protected areas in the ecoregion include [[Sooretama Biological Reserve]] and [[Linhares Forest Reserve]].
