{{climate-stub}}

'''Ergosophy''' is a term coined by the scientist [[Frederick Soddy]], in the early 1920s, and refers to aspects of [[energy]] in relation to human existence and energy measurement as in ([[Erg]]s).<ref>{{cite book |title=The Role of Money |author=Frederick Soddy |publisher=[[Routledge]] |date=1934 |pages=256 |ISBN=978-0-415-48891-4 |accessdate=2009-10-18 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bI-BjmxzDrUC&pg=PA1&lpg=PA1&dq=Soddy+the+role+of+money+ergosophy&source=bl&ots=DXGANGwFYt&sig=9kfmT4ANFJr-P1OkHFGRRvm7GFA&hl=sv&ei=VC3bSvKHLsT4-AbMxLXBDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=&f=false }}</ref> Soddy's aim was to apply science theories and ideas and move the human understanding of work beyond the restrictions of [[management theory]] into a new theory of [[energy economics]].
Frederick Soddy first used the term in his book on work and economics: ''The Role of Money''.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Role of Money |author=Frederick Soddy |publisher=Routledge |date=1934 |pages=256 |ISBN=978-0-415-48891-4 |accessdate=2009-10-18 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bI-BjmxzDrUC&pg=PA1&lpg=PA1&dq=Soddy+the+role+of+money+ergosophy&source=bl&ots=DXGANGwFYt&sig=9kfmT4ANFJr-P1OkHFGRRvm7GFA&hl=sv&ei=VC3bSvKHLsT4-AbMxLXBDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=&f=false }}</ref>
